<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Nazgul Conditions are Dominant<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.22)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10558'>Ulaire "Morgul Minas" Lemenya</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10558&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 25, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Every Shadow Culture has conditions which are powerful. Moria have They Are Coming, Goblin Swarms and Goblin Armory. Sauron have Orc Bowmen and UTWE. Isengard have Worry, Greed and Sarumans various things. All of these are good and useful. But of all the conditions in the game none are as scary as the Nazgul ones.<br />
<br />
Ok, Nazgul don&#39;t have that many conditions and many of them are not that good. Bent on Discovery, Drawn to its Power, The Nine Servants of Sauron, Not Easily Destroyed, Paths Seldom Travelled, Wreathed in Shadow, Helpless and His Terrible Servants are all only useful in some citcumstances. I will briefly discuss them.<br />
<br />
Bent on Discovery - drawing a card is nice but exerting a Nazgul sucks. If you can&#39;t you lose the condition. I have never seen this played.<br />
<br />
Drawn to its Power - not very strong by itself but can be a good part of a burden deck. I have always wanted to make a deck with 4 of them in and then when I kill Pippin I get to add 4 burdens! Trouble is it is hard to find 4 card slots that don&#39;t actually help you do anything until you KILL someone. Not in many decks.<br />
<br />
The Nine Servants of Sauron - now while this seems a little weak it has some really good uses. Exerting Merry from 4 wounds to 3 is a waste of time, but putting Bounder from 2 to 1 might just win you the game. Trouble is if they have no Hobbits you have a worthless card. Most people don&#39;t bother.<br />
<br />
Not Easily Destroyed - Remove 3 to heal a Nazgul? Are you kidding? If the culture already has one weakness it is the high cost of their minions. All Baldes Perish is much better.<br />
<br />
Paths Seldom Travelled - Another card that is much better done by another card. Nelya does this for free rather than costing 3 to do it. Did I mention that they are already short on twylight. The only time I can imagine this being used is in a dedicated Twylight Nazgul deck where they use Nelya RIT instead of Nelya LOM.<br />
<br />
Wreathed in Shadow - Well at least this card is playable. Cost 0 and 1 to use is good. Trouble is most archery decks these days use directed archery. Still not a bad card for cost 0. If you find you are up against a lot of elves or later in the game when Aragorn and Legolas GL are exhausted it can be very useful. <br />
<br />
Helpless - Really seems like a pathetic card but if you are doing a twylight burden deck the last thing you want is Sam removing all of those burdens you put so much effort into creating. Sam is still by far the most popular burden removal tool. In fact he probably removes 90% of all of the burdens that get removed in LOTR. So if you are trying for a burden victory this is an almost essential support card.<br />
<br />
His Terrible Servants - What Not Easily Destroyed should have been. Cost 1 to avoid a wound is quite reasonable especially after some sucky ranger has ARV&#39;d you. Only affects Twylight Nazgul but some people do play twylight Nazgul only (or almost only) decks. If that is your deck this is good.<br />
<br />
So my initial contention is that the Nazgul conditions are dominant is looking bad isn&#39;t it? Oh wait I seem to have forgotten two little conditions: Blade Tip and Black Breath.<br />
<br />
It is these two conditions that totally change everything and affect every deck in the game. For a cost of 0 and 1 you can ensure a companion WILL die unless they have some condition removal.<br />
<br />
Why does every second deck carry Athelas? Don&#39;t tell me it is for the 1 point of healing. It is for these two cards. Why is Sleep Caradhras so popular? It kills these. Why is Bilbo popping up in every Dwarf deck now? Why do some decks have more Secret Sentinals than Elf companions? Sure these are great to unload a full Goblin Swarm but we know the real reason. Who hasn&#39;t lost a game because at site 3 someone crucial gets tipped and bad breath?<br />
<br />
They are so devastating that they often can completly disrupt an opponents strategy. They are using directed archery? How will that work when Legolas takes a wound at the start of each turn? Playing Dwarves? They can have 4x Till Durin Wakes Agains out and it wont help Gimli if he has Black Breath. They have Aragorn with No Stranger, his bow, sword, brand and the last alliance annoying you. He needs one of each and soon he will go away.<br />
<br />
I have seen people make the worst mistakes just because of these conditions. Boromir has Blade Tip and so my opponent figures he will die next turn anyway so he moves on. I overwhelm Frodo and win the game.  Aragon has Black Breath and so they don&#39;t want him to even take one wound because they can heal it, so they let Legolas fight the Nazgul. I play Threshold of Shadow and he dies. People panic when these hit the table. They play Sleep and get rid of 2x No Stranger to remove one Blade Tip. They sacrifice people they dont need to - &quot;ah Arwen can fight the Balrog, she&#39;s going to die anyway.&quot;<br />
<br />
One of the tactics in the game is to put your opponent under pressure. To make them not move when they should, to rush ahead when they really shouldn&#39;t. What does that better than these?<br />
<br />
Now what I really don&#39;t understand is that some players don&#39;t use these conditions. Why? Too expensive? No. Gotten rid of with Sleep C? Great, that adds 3 to the pool and exerts Gandalf. They would rather some more minions? One of the difficult things you need to do with Nazgul is get a balance between cheap and expensive cards. Cost 0 is fairly cheap. I am not saying you have to use 4 of each of them but surely you can find room in your deck for at least two each of the most scary conditions in the game. Can&#39;t you?<br />
<br />
Now go and find the ring. <br />
<br />
